    rationale: "Thyroid hormones regulate metabolic rate throughout the body, including the gastrointestinal tract. In hypothyroidism, reduced thyroid hormone levels slow colonic smooth muscle activity and decrease the frequency and amplitude of peristaltic contractions, prolonging intestinal transit time and causing constipation. This is a systemic metabolic effect, not a direct neural or electrolyte mechanism. Hypothyroidism does not primarily cause hypokalemia. TSH does not directly inhibit enteric acetylcholine release. Sympathetic activity is not the primary mechanism here.",
