    rationale: "Acetylcholine acting on muscarinic (M3) receptors in intestinal smooth muscle is the primary driver of propulsive peristalsis. Anticholinergic drugs block these muscarinic receptors, reducing the cholinergic stimulation of intestinal smooth muscle and impairing coordinated peristaltic contractions. The result is slowed colonic transit and constipation. Anticholinergics do not increase sympathetic tone or block nicotinic receptors at therapeutic doses. Reduced gastric acid secretion (via M1 blockade) does not significantly impair transit.",
